		<div id="post_message_1247066">
                  
                  Torcer, I think she made the wrong choice as much as you do, but ...<br />
<br />
Given that she believes a transfusion is a mortal sin, taking it would separate her from her children <i>forever</i>. Yes she no doubt knew it was likely they would grow up motherless. But she also likely believed that this way she will see them again, that she will be able to watch over them, etc. On the other hand, taking the transfusion means at best, if she lived, she would get to raise them at the cost of them losing their mother for all eternity.<br />
<br />
I'm happy to say it's a stupid belief. But you have to argue against the belief itself, you aren't going to get any traction by saying to the witness, &quot;but you are abandoning your children, that is evil&quot;, because sometimes doing something that will result in abandoning your children is the right thing to do. Not often, but sometimes, and if the Witnesses were right, this would be one of those cases.
                  
		</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
